<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-11-17T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-11-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="503" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d503">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 365.117/459</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Ambassador <persName type="from">Page</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Rome</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-11-17">
                                    <hi rend="italic">November 17, 1916</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>733. Department’s 324, April 18. Military authorities hold that, while
                            Orocchi may have lost Italian citizenship during minority <pb facs="0504" n="428" xml:id="pg_428"/> owing to naturalization his
                            father, nevertheless, this fact does not exempt him from military
                            obligations towards Kingdom according terms Article 12, Civil Code, held
                            to be applicable in his case.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Nelson Page</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>